It is well known that the maximal fluorescent property can only be achieved when the CCDs are homogeneously dispersed in their host polymer matrix because the aggregation would lead to a luminescence quenching of CCDs [3]. We therefore firstly studied the CCDs dispersion in the rubber composites. A simple visual inspection for the rubber films is shown in Fig. 3
                        , the SiR film without CCDs is obviously translucent. No CCDs aggregates were observed in the SiR/χCCDs composites by naked eyes, and the SiR/χCCDs films are turning ever more yellow with the increase of CCDs. The light transmittance ratio for the SiR/χCCDs samples was also measured using UV spectrophotometer (Fig. 4
                        ), it shows that the light transmittance of SiR/χCCDs samples were inevitably decreased with the increase of CCDs, demonstrating the inclusion of deep-colored CCDs into SiR would inevitably decrease the transparency.

We further used the optical microscope to study the SiR/χCCDs films (Fig. 5
                        ), no obvious CCDs aggregation in SiR/χCCDs composites could be observed, which is in accordance with the visual inspection mentioned above. The fine CCDs dispersion within the host matrix is because the liquid feeding of CCDs fluid allows preserving the individualization state of the molecules/particles in CCDs resulting from their colloidal dispersion in water. In another word, the H2O in the CCDs fluid could weaken the interactions between CCDs particles/molecules [29], and simultaneously the favorable interactions (H-bonding) between silica and CCDs (illustrated in Fig. 6
                        ) facilitate the uniformly dispersion of CCDs within the SiR matrix [30,31].
